@NODE INTRO "Introduction to NetDock"
  
   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Introduction to NetDock@{FG TEXT}

   Hi, welcome to the wonderful world of NetDock! This program has been
   created for the average Internet Amigan (like myself!) But why did I
   make it?

     On a recent Amiga Format CD, I noticed a program called VitalConnect.
   This program was similar to this, but used 256 colours for the user
   interface, and required the programs it used to be in the main 
   VitalConnect drawer. If I remember, there wasn't any configuration
   options either.

     I did use VC for a while, but then I discovered that the 256 colour
   UI (required to make it look decent) was eating up too much of my
   precious Chip RAM. I also wanted a seperate Internet drawer on my
   Workbench partition. So I set about producing a 'rival' to VC.

     After a few weeks planning and coding, NetDock was born. The
   program was written in Blitz Basic 2 from ACID Software. It uses an
   8 colour User Interface by default, although you can design buttons
   with more colours (see @{"imagesets" LINK IMAGE})

     Then I found that I needed a prefs program to manage the paths easily.
   So, after another day or so's coding, PathPrefs was finished. This
   allowed easy alteration of program paths.

     And that's pretty much the whole story. There were a few bugs which
   I couldn't fix, so turned to the @{"Blitz mailing list" LINK BMLIST} for help, and
   I received that help in about a day (thanx guys!)

   @{" Back to Main Menu " LINK MAIN}@{"System Requirements" LINK SYSTEM}
@ENDNODE

@NODE SYSTEM "System Requirements"
   
   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}System Requirements@{FG TEXT}

   NetDock and PathPrefs are not really fussy about the system you are
   using (I hope!) but the basic requirements are:-

      · An 8-colour workbench (or more colours if you want)
      · About 80K of available RAM
      · Some Internet programs (no more than 8 can be used though)
      · The NetDock: assign pointing to the NetDock directory.

   And that's it! Note that if you have more than 8 programs on your
   machine, you can only configure NetDock for 8 of those at a time.
   If you don't have 8, then just leave the others as they are.

   @{" Back to Main Menu " LINK MAIN}@{"   Installation    " LINK INSTALL}
@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "Installation"

   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Installation@{FG TEXT}

   Installing NetDock is simple. In fact, it's so simple I don't even need
   to write an Installer script for it! Just follow these TWO steps:-

      · Copy the ENTIRE CONTENTS of the NetDock distribution drawer to
        wherever you want.

      · Load up your S:user-startup file in your favourite text editor
        and add this line to it:

              Assign NetDock: <DEV><DIR><SUBDIR>

        where <DEV> is the device name, e.g. DH1: or Work:
        and <DIR> is the directory, e.g. Utilities/
        and <SUBDIR> is the NetDock dir, i.e. NetDock/

        so the whole line looks like this (just an example)

            Assign NetDock: Work:Utilities/NetDock

   and that's it! NetDock is now installed on your system. If you do have
   problems getting NetDock to work, then contact me and I will help you
   out. My e-mail address is gaz@jokerd.idps.co.uk and my snail-mail
   address is:-
   
                             Joker Developments
                             26 Buttington Road
                                 SHREWSBURY
                                 Shropshire
                                  SY2 5TS, 
                                  ENGLAND.

   I will get back to you as soon as I can. If you think there should be
   an Installer script, then contact me at the same addresses.

   @{" Back to Main Menu " LINK MAIN}@{"Registering NetDock" LINK UPDATE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UPDATE "Registering NetDock"

   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Registering NetDock@{FG TEXT}
  
   The unregistered version of NetDock does not allow you to change the
   imageset, and there are nag requesters on startup and exit. These are
   the ONLY limitations. 

   To register NetDock, simply send a cheque for Ł5.00 (Great British
   pounds only please!) made payable to Gareth Griffiths to:

   Gareth Griffiths
   26 Buttington Road
   SHREWSBURY
   Shropshire
   SY2 5TS
   ENGLAND

   And if you have an e-mail address, include that so that I can get the
   full version to you even quicker. ALWAYS include your snail-mail address
   for my reference. If I do not get a snail-mail address, your cheque 
   will NOT be cashed (it will be destroyed), and you won't receive the 
   full version.

   The REGISTERED version does away with the nag requesters, and gives you
   info on your memory situations, and on the current imageset, which you
   can change. It also allows you to enter into the 'design an imageset'
   competition, which is only available for registered users.
 
   @{" Back to Main Menu " LINK MAIN}@{"   Using NetDock   " LINK USAGE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE USAGE "Using NetDock"
 
   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Using NetDock@{FG TEXT}

   Using the program itself is really simple. To start the program, you
   can do so from either Workbench or CLI:
 
    @{B}To launch from Workbench:@{UB}
      Just double-click on the NetDock icon. It does work better if
      you put it in the WBStartup directory on your hard drive.

    @{B}To launch from CLI:@{UB}
      Use the CD command to go to the NetDock directory, e.g.

          CD Work:Utilities/NetDock

      and then type in 'Run >NIL: NetDock' (excluding the quotes) and
      press RETURN. The NetDock window should appear.

   There are a number of error messages which can be generated on startup.
   They usually mean that a certain file cannot be found. Make sure that
   you have assigned NetDock: to the right place. 
     If you still cannot work out what's wrong, use a 'snooping' program
   such as Eddy Carroll's excellent SnoopDOS (available on Aminet) to find
   out which file is causing the problem.


   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}RIGHT! I've got the program started. What now?@{FG TEXT}
  
   The window should appear in the place defined by the 'windowpos' file in
   NetDock:Settings/. If it doesn't, then the window can not be opened in
   that position, so it defaults to the top left. In this window there are
   8 buttons. They will be drawn in the default imageset. Clicking on 
   one of these buttons will launch the program specified in the 'progpaths'
   file. Note that the button images may not correspond with the programs.
   This is not MY fault, it is whoever designed the images being used, and
   the person who set the paths. The default paths and images are perfect.

   To exit the program, click on the Close gadget in the top left of the
   window. Alternatively, you could hold down the RIGHT mouse button, and
   select Quit from the NetDock menu. Speaking of menus...


   @{FG HIGHLIGHT}The NetDock menus@{FG TEXT}

   NetDock has a simple menu system. These are accessed by holding down
   the right mouse button (as you would do in Workbench) and manoeuvring
   the mouse over to one of the menus. There are two menus:-

      @{B}NetDock@{UB}
        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Edit Program Paths...@{FG TEXT}
        This calls up the PathPrefs program, and lets you edit the
        program path assignments used when you click on a button.
        See PathPrefs.guide for information on how to use PathPrefs.

        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Snapshot Window@{FG TEXT}
        Saves the current window position to 'NetDock:Settings/windowpos'
        This file is read on startup, allowing you to permanently put the
        window somewhere (or until you snapshot the window again)

        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}About NetDock...@{FG TEXT}
        Displays a simple about box, which repeats 25 times. This nag
        factor is removed in the REGISTERED version of NetDock!

        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}Quit@{FG TEXT}
        Displays a confirmation requester, and if given OK as a response,
        does the 25 about boxes, and then quits NetDock and frees any
        used memory (except for libraries)

      @{B}Help@{UB}
        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}NetDock Help...@{FG TEXT}
        Displays this AmigaGuide file.
  
        @{FG HIGHLIGHT}PathPrefs Help...@{FG TEXT}
        Displays the PathPrefs.guide file.

